### How to read Figure 3

- The **solid colored polygon** is the "fingerprint" of the FAC group — ideally a compact pentagon centered on the median cadence.
- The **shaded ring around the polygon** shows the spread (±1 SD). A thin ring means the sensors agree tightly within that group; a thick or irregular ring means some sensors deviate.
- Compare the **size** of the three polygons across groups: higher FAC → larger polygon (higher cadence).
- Compare the **regularity** across groups: a distorted pentagon reveals that some sensors (the "long branches") give systematically different values.

## Figure 4 — Bland-Altman plots: inter-sensor agreement

The Bland-Altman plot is the gold-standard method to assess **agreement** (not just absence of difference) between two measurement methods. For each sample we plot:

- **x-axis**: mean of the two sensors (the "true" cadence estimate)
- **y-axis**: difference between the two sensors
- **solid line**: mean difference (bias)
- **dashed lines**: limits of agreement (LoA) = bias ± 1.96 × SD of differences

**Interpretation**:

- Narrow LoA → the two sensors can be used interchangeably in clinical practice
- Wide LoA → the sensors disagree substantially on some samples
- Bias ≠ 0 → one sensor systematically over- or under-estimates compared to the other
- We stratify by FAC group to reveal whether agreement **degrades in low-FAC patients** (the hypothesis that low-autonomy patients are more sensitive to sensor placement).

Four clinically relevant pairs are compared:

1. **LF vs RF** — left/right symmetry of foot measurements
2. **LW vs RW** — left/right symmetry of wrist measurements
3. **LF vs SA** — foot vs sacrum (both clinically recommended placements)
4. **LF vs LW** — foot vs wrist (reveals harmonic-capture artifacts)

```{r viz-bland-altman-function}
#' Build a Bland-Altman dataframe for two sensors
build_ba_data <- function(df_wide, sens1, sens2) {
  col1 <- paste0("cadence_", sens1)
  col2 <- paste0("cadence_", sens2)
  df_wide %>%
    filter(!is.na(.data[[col1]]) & !is.na(.data[[col2]])) %>%
    mutate(
      mean_val = (.data[[col1]] + .data[[col2]]) / 2,
      diff_val = .data[[col1]] - .data[[col2]],
      pair     = paste0(sens1, " vs ", sens2)
    ) %>%
    select(sample_id, FAC, mean_val, diff_val, pair)
}

#' Compute bias and limits of agreement per FAC group
compute_loa <- function(ba_df) {
  ba_df %>%
    group_by(FAC_group, pair) %>%
    summarise(
      n        = n(),
      bias     = mean(diff_val, na.rm = TRUE),
      sd_diff  = sd(diff_val, na.rm = TRUE),
      loa_low  = bias - 1.96 * sd_diff,
      loa_high = bias + 1.96 * sd_diff,
      .groups  = "drop"
    ) %>%
    mutate(
      sd_diff  = ifelse(is.na(sd_diff), 0, sd_diff),
      loa_low  = ifelse(is.na(loa_low),  bias, loa_low),
      loa_high = ifelse(is.na(loa_high), bias, loa_high)
    )
}
```

```{r viz-bland-altman-data}
df_wide_ok <- df_wide %>% filter(!(sample_id %in% samples_to_exclude))

pairs_to_plot <- list(
  c("LF", "RF"),
  c("LW", "RW"),
  c("LF", "SA"),
  c("LF", "LW")
)

ba_all <- purrr::map_dfr(
  pairs_to_plot,
  ~ build_ba_data(df_wide_ok, .x[1], .x[2])
) %>%
  apply_FAC_grouping() %>%
  mutate(pair = factor(pair,
                       levels = sapply(pairs_to_plot, function(p) paste(p, collapse = " vs "))))

loa_all <- compute_loa(ba_all)

cat("-- Bias and 95% Limits of Agreement per FAC group and sensor pair --\n")
print(loa_all %>% mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ round(.x, 3))))

write_csv(loa_all, file.path(OUTPUT_DIR, "bland_altman_loa.csv"))
